<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"  xml:id="functionchapter">
  <title>Differentiation</title>
  <introduction>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
      <em>Despite the saying that <q>for every epsilon there is a delta,</q> (which is really rather romantic, when you think about it) I often could not get my epsilons paired off with suitable deltas.</em>
      </p>
      <attribution>
        Herbert Wilf (1931<ndash/>2012)
      </attribution>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      We will now start our study of complex functions.
      <em>The</em> fundamental concept on which all of calculus is
      based is that of a limit<mdash/>it allows us to develop the
      central properties of continuity and differentiability of
      functions. 
      Our goal in this chapter is to do the same for complex functions.
    </p>
  </introduction>
